# Isometric log ratio transformations for the dwell time and % dwell time data My reasoning is that because ILR represents a datapoint’s coordinate in a k-1 dimensional space, k needs to be 2 for this to be a meaningful analysis unit. So ILR needs to be performed on p and mag+fix or on m and p+fix or on fix and p+m (z, zz and zzz, respectively). ILRs based on dwell times vs. % dwell times are essentially the same.

par(mfrow=c(2,2))

Dwell time and % dwell time as predictors

Lower probabilitie (more difficult decisions) are associated with more dwelling on probability information. Overall, when people spend a long time deliberating a choice, they spend more time looking at probabilities and magnitudes and proportionally more time looking at probabilities. When they spend little time deliberating, they proportionately look more at fixations.

The proportion of gaze at probabilities is pretty much entirely determined by EVR and does not vary as a function of safe vs risky choice. However, people look longer at magnitudes for risky choices at riskier EVRs.Can test the hypothesis whether looking at magnitudes interacts with cues to predict riskier choice.
